I get it that the older Wade-Giles romanization spelling system has largely been replaced in most of the world with (Hanyu) Pinyin (it seems in Taiwan the former is still widely used, though not officially). However, NYT xworders should be aware that TAO is still much more often the answer to some kind of eastern/Chinese way clue( 297 appearances). 
DAO has appeared only 31 times, usually clued as a large Philippine tree.  Today is the debut use of DAO in reference a “way”, and it was specifically signaled by the reference to Pinyin.

